\intbl \ql \b Background\b0 \line The Oakfields College \'28Pty\'29 Ltd is registered with the Department of Higher Education and Training as a private higher education institution and has programmes accredited by the CHE.\line \line The Institution applied for accreditation of the Higher Certificate in Sound Technology which was tabled at the AC meeting held on the 28th of September 2022 and HEQC meeting held on the 4th of November 2022.\line \line The proposed programme will be offered at the following sites of delivery\'3A\line - Lynnridge Mall\'2C Pretoria\line - Stoneridge Mall\'2C Johannesburg\'2C East Rand.\line \line According to the Register of Private Higher Education Institutions \'28DHET\'2C 3 May 2023\'29\'2C there are currently four contact learning programmes offered at the Pretoria site and two at the Johannesburg site. Besides the addition of this contact Higher Certificate programme\'2C the following CL programmes \'28currently in process\'29 will also be offered at these sites\'2C if accredited\'3A\line - Higher Certificate in Make-up and SFX Design \'28outstanding prior-to-commencement conditions\'29\line - Higher Certificate in Graphic Design \'28representation\'29\line - Higher Certificate in Fundamentals of Filmmaking \'28representation\'29\line - Higher Certificate in Fashion Design Development \'28representation\'29\line - Higher Certificate in Photography \'28outstanding prior-to-commencement conditions\'29.\line \line The last site visit was conducted in 2014\'2C at the Pretoria site.\line \line The Higher Certificate in Sound Technology programme was not accredited for the following reasons\'3A\line 1. The programme design does not meet the vocational and entry-level requirements for a Higher Certificate at NQF level 5\'2C namely the provision of the fundamental skills followed up by \'28the\'29 development and application of professional skills. Too much emphasis is placed on theory to the detriment of practical application.\line 2. It is not clear how the modules will lead to the achievement of the programme purpose or how the modules will collectively contribute to the development of Sound Technology skills for graduates. Some modules are unrelated to the core requirements of skills and competencies in Sound Technology.\line 3. A clear understanding of acoustics and psychoacoustics is missing from the programme\'2C which is essential to the development of a sound technologist. There is insufficient focus on the principles of the field of sound technology and too much emphasis on specific technologies \'2F software.\line 4. The programme lacks transition in logic and design from one module to the next and there is no learning progression towards sound technology evident. Furthermore\'2C the scope of Music Theory and Practice is insufficient for a programme with its core focus on Sound Technology. It is also unclear how students will create sound or music without knowledge about the aural\'2C artistic\'2C stylistic\'2C and structural elements of the creation.\line 5. The articulation options are limited and inaccurate in some cases. References to Engineering in all aspects of the programme\'2C including articulation\'2C are incorrect. The reference to an Advanced Certificate is wrong as this is a short learning programme.\line 6. The academic staff are not appropriately and adequately qualified to teach the core modules in Sound Technology. \line 7. The workload distribution is demanding and makes little allowance for staff development.\line \line The Institution submitted a representation which has been evaluated.\cell \pard 

