\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The summary of the evaluation per reason for non-accreditation follows below.\line \line 1 \'26 2. Programme design\'3B Modules and structure\'3A\line \line There is a fair balance of practical to theory in the modular design of the qualification. In terms of theory vs practical application\'2C the programme is more practically oriented\'2C with a significant focus on equipping students with Sound Technology skills that can be directly applied in that specific job role. The programme does lean towards practical skills\'2C but some foundational theory is included to provide context and understanding of the subject matter. According to the evaluator\'2C the explanation is sound. The evaluator is of the view that it is evident that the modules are intentionally structured and interrelated\'2C and they collectively contribute to the overall development of the required skills in Sound Technology. The Institution provided a clear explanation of how each module relates to\'2C and supports\'2C the core requirements of skills and competencies in Sound Technology. The reasons have been addressed.\line \line 3. Sound technology and acoustics\'3A\line \line The Institution acknowledged that there was room for improvement in the theoretical elements of Sound Theory in the module\'27s content. The aim of the course was to focus more on practical application of sound technologies\'2C but there is a need for more emphasis on in-depth principles such as acoustics and psychoacoustics. The programme will meet criterion 1 if it is adjusted and improved to expand on the in-depth principles related to sound technology and acoustics. The reason has not been adequately addressed.\line \line 4. Transition in logic and design\'2C learning progression to sound technology\'2C and music theory and practice\'3A\line \line Regarding the programme\'27s logical progression\'2C transition\'2C and scope of the Music Theory and Practice module\'2C the Institution has undertaken substantial revision to address these issues. The evaluator is satisfied that these have been successfully revised. The Institution has also reconsidered the content of the Music Theory and Practice module. It now encompasses a broader range of elements related to music and its creation\'2C thereby reinforcing its relevance and contribution to the primary focus on Sound Technology. The reason has been addressed.\line \line 5. Articulation\'3A\line \line The Institution acknowledges that there were errors in the articulation options submitted\'2C and has provided clarification on its intention to apply for an Advanced Certificate in Sound Production as a future articulation pathway. Importantly\'2C the Institution acknowledges that it may not promote or refer to any qualifications which have not yet been accredited\'2C thereby demonstrating adherence to the correct protocol. The pathways facilitated by other institutions have proven to be suitably comprehensive. The proposed articulation pathways\'2C as presented in the initial application\'2C are adequate.\line \line 6. Academic staff\'3A\line \line The Institution has indicated that\'2C while primarily offering SETA-accredited programmes\'2C it recognises the need for specialised staff in the event of accreditation and an increase in enrolment numbers for this particular programme. A detailed plan for hiring the appropriate teaching and support staff has been developed\'2C including an organogram and a comprehensive workload model.\line \line 7. Workload and staff development\'3A\line \line The workload model takes into account the various roles an academic staff member may have\'2C including teaching\'2C research\'2C and administrative duties. In cases where a staff member is contracted for teaching only\'2C the workload is carefully balanced between teaching responsibilities and administrative duties. The workload model addresses the distribution of hours across the tasks for each academic staff member. This ensures that each staff member\'27s workload is well managed and distributed. The Institution has demonstrated a clear commitment to staff development\'2C as outlined in the Staff Development Policy. It is dedicated to training and developing its employees in alignment with the dynamic needs of the educational environment\'2C development needs of the employees\'2C and legislative requirements. This commitment is reinforced by the staff development plan. The reason has been addressed.\line \line The Directorate recommends that the programme should be accredited with conditions.\cell \pard 

